{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503388"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:59:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:59:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2024"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2024"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.58,0.26,0.06,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2024"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110386"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2024"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2024"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92659"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"1477"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11102"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11160"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33565"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37273"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41114"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110386"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 59-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of sudden-onset severe eye pain, redness, and decreased vision in his left eye. He underwent uncomplicated cataract surgery seven days ago in the same eye. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed with vital signs within normal limits. His visual acuity is reduced to counting fingers at one metre in the affected eye. There is marked conjunctival injection, corneal oedema, and a 2 mm hypopyon. The pupil is poorly reactive to light. Fundoscopic examination is limited due to media opacity but reveals vitreous haze.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral moxifloxacin","Intravitreal ceftazidime and vancomycin","Intravitreal dexamethasone","Oral ciprofloxacin","Intravitreal amphotericin B"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute postoperative endophthalmitis following cataract surgery. The combination of severe eye pain, decreased vision, hypopyon, and vitreous inflammation within one week of surgery is characteristic of this sight-threatening condition. Immediate treatment is crucial to preserve vision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravitreal ceftazidime and vancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate immediate management. This combination provides broad-spectrum coverage against both Gram-positive organisms (including \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus epidermidis\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E) and Gram-negative organisms. Intravitreal administration achieves therapeutic concentrations within the vitreous cavity immediately, which is essential given the poor penetration of systemic antibiotics into the vitreous. A vitreous tap should ideally be performed before antibiotic injection to obtain samples for culture and sensitivity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral moxifloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral ciprofloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E are fluoroquinolone antibiotics with some vitreous penetration. While these agents may be considered as a temporising measure when immediate access to intravitreal therapy is not available, they should never substitute for urgent intravitreal antibiotics. In cases of exogenous endophthalmitis where significant delays in accessing specialist care are anticipated, oral fluoroquinolones may be commenced after consultation with an ophthalmologist, but the patient must still be urgently transferred for definitive intravitreal therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravitreal dexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E is sometimes used as adjunctive therapy to reduce inflammation in endophthalmitis, but it should never be used as monotherapy. Corticosteroids without concurrent antibiotics could potentially worsen the infection by suppressing the local immune response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravitreal amphotericin B\u003C/strong\u003E is an antifungal agent used for fungal endophthalmitis. While fungal endophthalmitis can occur after cataract surgery, it typically presents more indolently over weeks to months rather than acutely within seven days. Bacterial endophthalmitis is far more common in this timeframe and requires antibacterial therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPost-cataract endophthalmitis occurs in fewer than one in 3000 cases but requires urgent recognition and treatment. The most common causative organisms are coagulase-negative staphylococci, though Gram-negative organisms and fungi can also be responsible. Following intravitreal antibiotics, patients require close monitoring and may need repeat injections or vitrectomy if there is no improvement within 48 hours.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Timely recognition and intervention are paramount in managing post-cataract surgery endophthalmitis to prevent irreversible vision loss.","Intravitreal antibiotics with broad-spectrum coverage (ceftazidime and vancomycin) are the first-line treatment for acute postoperative endophthalmitis.","Oral fluoroquinolones may be initiated if transfer to specialist care is delayed, but should not replace urgent intravitreal therapy."],"references":["Durand ML. Bacterial and Fungal Endophthalmitis. Clin Microbiol Rev. 2017; 30: 597\u2013613","Sharma N, Ooi JL, Li MZ, Wechsler D. Acute infective endophthalmitis--case studies in ophthalmic emergencies. Aust Fam Physician. 2012 Jun;41(6):395-6. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22675679/","Endophthalmitis. Therapeutic Guidelines [database online]. West Melbourne, VIC: Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd; 2019 Apr. Accessed 2025 Jul 30."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92659"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2024"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92659"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-30T16:38:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-30T16:38:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2024"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110386"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1193"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Eye pain","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-07-31T01:47:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:43:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"3"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1477"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Endophthalmitis","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-11-14T22:37:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T11:31:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"contributions","id":"11102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/contributions/11102"},"attributes":{"finalizedAt":"2024-03-16T17:49:10+10:30","userDetails":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2024"}},"contributionTier":{"data":{"type":"contributionTiers","id":"2"}},"user":{"data":null},"contributionType":{"data":{"type":"contributionTypes","id":"2"}}}},{"type":"contributions","id":"11160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/contributions/11160"},"attributes":{"finalizedAt":"2024-03-16T17:49:10+10:30","userDetails":{"name":"John Crompton","title":"Prof","isExpert":true,"position":"Ophthalmologist","training":"Consult